b'' b'' b'how hard is a carb rebuild for moderately experienced backyard mechanic?' b"i've done my clutch and miscellaneous little engine fixes." b'' b'the hardest part is usually getting the darned thing off the intake' b"manifold. rebuilding a carb is fun, if you're into things with" b"lots of little parts. i used to rebuild them for all my friends'" b"cars in high school, so it doesn't take a phd. buy a carb rebuilding" b'kit from an auto supply store. buy a gallon of the best carb cleaning' b'solvent you can find (do they still make tyme?) as a rule of thumb,' b'buy the one with the scariest warning labels. put it into a metal(!)' b'bucket. make yourself a dipping can by punching holes in the bottom of' b'a coffee can and attaching a wire handle to it. if the carb cleaner' b"doesn't strip the paint right off the coffee can, you're not" b'using the right stuff. use the can to soak the little stuff, and' b'just hang the big parts from a coat hanger. wash them off with a' b'garden hose, wipe off excess water with paper towels, and air dry.' b'then remember where all the little parts go. follow the rebuild' b"kit's instructions concerning float height, choke tension, etc." b'bolt it back on the engine and admire the super-clean carb on the' b'filthy engine.' b'' b"heed this man's warnings! if you get carb cleaner this strong on" b'your hands, your hands will be eaten away. not pretty. hence the "dipping' b'can" method.' b'' b'later,' b'--' b"chris behanna\tdod# h-d fxwg wide glide jubilee's red lady" b'disclaimer: now why would nec\t zx-11 needs a name' b'agree with any of this anyway? i was raised by a pack of wild corn dogs.' 